{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
The '''Allgemeines bürgerliches Gesetzbuch''' ('''ABGB''') is the [[Civil Code]] of [[Austria]], which was enacted in 1811 after about 40 years of preparatory works. Karl Anton Freiherr von Martini and Franz von Zeiller were the leading drafters at the earlier and later stages of the draft. Comparable to the [[Napoleonic code]], it was based on the ideals of freedom and equality before the law. It was divided into three major segments, following the [[Roman law]] segregation methods. It was modernized during the [[First World War]]. ABGB continues to be the basic civil code of [[Austria]] to this day and it is also still the basic civil code of [[Liechtenstein]]. Besides Austria, its influence persists in other successor states of [[Austria-Hungary]]. In the Czech part of [[Czechoslovakia]] (The Slovak part used Hungarian customary law) it was in effect until 1951, although it had been [[Novation|novelized]] multiple times, until it was replaced by the civil code from 1950.

