{{Infobox newspaper | name = Basarabia | logo = | image = | caption = | type = newspaper | format = | owners = | founder = | publisher = | editor = | chiefeditor = | assoceditor = | maneditor = | newseditor = | managingeditordesign = | campuseditor = | campuschief = | opeditor = | sportseditor = | photoeditor = | staff = | foundation = 1906 | political = | language = [[Romanian language|Romanian]] | ceased publication = 1907 | headquarters = [[Chişinău]] | circulation = | sister newspapers = [[Viaţa Basarabiei, 1907|Viaţa Basarabiei]] | ISSN = | oclc = | website = }}
'''''Basarabia''''' was the first [[Romanian language]] newspaper to be published in [[Bessarabia in the Russian Empire|Bessarabian guberniya]] of the [[Russian Empire]] in 1906-1907.
==History== [[File:May 1931, celebrating 25 years since the launch Basarabia, the first Romanian newspaper.jpg|thumb|left|In May 1931 the founders and employees of Basarabia celebrated 25 years since the launch]]
It was written with the [[Romanian Cyrillic alphabet]] and published twice weekly. Labeling itself a "national-democratic gazette", the newspaper asked within its articles for [[land reform]], autonomy and self-government for [[Bessarabia]] and the usage of Moldovan in schools and administration. It published articles by [[Constantin Stere]], [[Ion Inculeţ]], [[Ion Pelivan]], [[Alexei Mateevici]], and [[Pan Halippa]].<ref name="king29">*Charles King, ''The Moldovans: Romania, Russia, and the Politics of Culture'', 2000, Hoover Institution Press. {{ISBN|0-8179-9791-1}}, p.29</ref>
On March 1, 1907, the newspaper published the Romanian patriotic song "[[Deşteaptă-te, române!]]" ("Awaken thee, Romanian!"), which prompted the governor, [[Alexei Kharuzin]], to order its closure. The Russian noble families and the Russian Orthodox Church began a campaign of purging Romanian nationalists from the church and cultural institutions. Many of the supporters of the newspaper were forced to flee to [[Iaşi]], in [[Romania]], where Stere helped them to become students at [[University of Iaşi]].<ref name="king29"/>
A more moderate attempt to continue ''Basarabia'''s work began in 1907, a publication named ''[[Viaţa Basarabiei, 1907|Viaţa Basarabiei]]'' led by [[Alexis Nour]], written in two versions: with Romanian Latin and [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] alphabets, but after just six issues (April 22 - May 25, 1907), it also ceased its publication.<ref name="king29"/><ref>{{ro icon}} [[Mircea Rusnac]], [http://www.istoria.md/articol/464/Rena%C5%9Fterea_cultural_na%C5%A3ional%C4%83_a_Basarabiei_%C3%AEn_perioada_%C5%A2arist%C4%83 Renaşterea cultural-naţională a Basarabiei în perioada Ţaristă]</ref>
