[[Image:Formosan Distribution en.png|thumb|250px|Pazeh people formerly lived in the central area of Taiwan, labeled by dark purple.]]

The '''Pazeh''' (or '''Pazih'''; 巴則海 or 巴宰) people, including the [[Kaxabu people|Kaxabu]], are the descendants of the [[Tsouic]] Pazeh-speaking [[indigenous people]] from [[Taichung]] and [[Miaoli County|Miaoli]] areas of [[Taiwan]]. Due to the processes of [[acculturation]] and cultural [[Cultural assimilation|assimilation]], the majority of [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] who identify themselves as Pazeh reside in the [[Ai-lan district]] (愛蘭地區) in the central city of [[Puli, Nantou|Puli]], [[Nantou County|Nantou]].<ref>http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2014/06/15/2003592824</ref>

==Current status==
The current Pazih community is located around the Ai-lan (愛蘭) [[Taiwanese Presbyterian Church]], which provides support for the Pazeh cultural revival and political mobilization. The Ai-lan Pazih are currently petitioning [[Government of the Republic of China|Taiwan's government]] for official status as a recognized [[Taiwanese Aborigines|Taiwanese Aboriginal]] ethnic group.

