{{Infobox building | name = Pinto's Loggia | native_name = It-Tribuna ta' Pinto | native_name_lang = mt | image = Pinto Arch.jpg | image_caption = View of Pinto's Loggia | coordinates = {{coord|35|52|35.2|N|14|28|36.1|E|display=inline}} | alternate_names = Pinto's Lodge | status = Intact | building_type = [[Loggia]] | architectural_style = | location = [[Qormi]], [[Malta]] | namesake = [[Manuel Pinto da Fonseca]] | completion_date = 1772 | owner = | material = [[Limestone]] }}
'''Pinto's Loggia''' or '''Pinto's Lodge''' ({{lang-mt|It-Tribuna ta' Pinto - Il-Loġġa ta' Pinto}}), is a [[loggia]] in [[Qormi]], [[Malta]]. It was built in 1772 to commemorate the 31st year of [[Manuel Pinto da Fonseca]]'s magistracy, and it is now a landmark and symbol of Qormi.
==History== Pinto's Loggia was built in 1772, marking the 31st year of the reign of [[Manuel Pinto da Fonseca]] as [[List of Princes and Grand Masters of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Grand Master]] of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St. John]]. Qormi had been granted city status as ''Città Pinto'' on 25 May 1743, and the city still bears Pinto's coat of arms as its symbol.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zammit|first1=Vincent|title=Il-Gran Mastri – Ġabra ta' Tagħrif dwar l-Istorja ta' Malta fi Żmienhom – It-Tieni Volum 1680–1798|date=1992|publisher=Valletta Publishing & Promotion Co. Ltd.|location=[[Valletta]]|pages=427–428|language=Maltese}}</ref> The structure is supported by four columns, and it is decorated with Pinto's coat of arms and a [[Latin]] inscription. According to tradition, Pinto used to sit in the loggia to shade himself while watching [[horse racing]],<ref name="lc">{{cite web|title=Important Residences|url=http://lc.gov.mt/Page.aspx?catid=70&pid=190&lid=1|website=lc.gov.mt|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424095734/http://lc.gov.mt/Page.aspx?catid=70&pid=190&lid=1|archivedate=24 April 2016}}</ref> but its original purpose is still unclear.<ref name="dlhwalks">{{cite book|last1=Twitchell-Waas|first1=Jeffrey|title=Ħal Qormi – Four walks through a historic city|date=2011|publisher=[[Din l-Art Ħelwa]]|location=[[Valletta]]|isbn=9789995731021|pages=43–44|url=http://dinlarthelwa.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/Qormi-Walks-9.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424094202/http://dinlarthelwa.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/Qormi-Walks-9.pdf|archivedate=24 April 2016}}</ref>
[[File:Pinto Farmhouse-stables and Loggia in Qormi.jpg|thumb|left|The farmhouse complex, used as stables]] The loggia was originally part of a large farmhouse complex which included stables for the Grand Master's horses, but the farmhouses were demolished in 1981 to make way for modern houses.<ref>{{cite web|title=Residenzi Importanti|url=http://lc.gov.mt/Page.aspx?catid=70&pid=190&lid=2|website=lc.gov.mt|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424103859/http://lc.gov.mt/Page.aspx?catid=70&pid=190&lid=2|archivedate=24 April 2016|language=Maltese}}</ref> The Parish Church of St. Sebastian was later built in the vicinity of the loggia.<ref name="dlhwalks"/>
The loggia was restored in 1987<ref>{{cite book|last1=Guillaumier|first1=Alfie|title=Bliet u Rħula Maltin|date=1987|publisher=Valletta Publishing & Promotion Co. Ltd.|location=[[Valletta]]|pages=609–610|language=Maltese}}</ref> in 2002 and again in 2018 by the Local Council.<ref name="lc"/> A [[street market]] is held in the street and square near the loggia every Saturday morning,<ref name="dlhwalks"/> and it also serves as a backdrop for the annual Ħal Qormi Day.<ref name="lc"/>
==Further reading== *Grima, Joseph F. (2008). [http://www.armarsansebastjan.org/?wpfb_dl=4 Il-Gran Mastru Emanuel Pinto de Fonseca]. ''Armar San Sebastjan''. [[Qormi]]. p. 99.
